John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scottish independent schools have traditionally provided excellent education. Looking at recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed until 2018, which is further strengthened by individual and group success in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in such institutions, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide the best possible services for students and parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers and the position they hold as world citizens.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and introduce customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought after subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
But if you speak his language, it will reach his heart."
This is an important reminder because we cannot rely solely on English if we are to build relationships and trust with those from other countries.
This year's exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have produced the best results from foreign languages.
68 percent of all students studying foreign language achieved a higher A degree (above 85 percent).
Based on the data collected from SCIS 74's member school, it can be shown that 72 percent of students received higher A degrees in Mandarin, while 72 students in German, 69 in French and 63 percent in Spanish achieved A degrees.
These results also support the fact that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as essential knowledge, which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today languages, as chosen objects, have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics, both in independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Committee on Employment and Vocational Training showed that 17 percent of employers say that filling empty positions is difficult due to a lack of language skills.
This also shows that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As knowledge of foreign languages is expected in more and more jobs, language skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career one chooses, if he has learned a foreign language, he will gain a lifetime of enduring knowledge from which he has a clear advantage.
The ability to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically gives a competitive advantage to a multilingual candidate.
According to a survey by YouGov, in which 4,000 adults were interviewed in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were not well enough in any foreign language to be able to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10% (15 percent) of respondents.
That is why it is important to focus on the language teaching of children at this time.
To speak more languages, especially in the language of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children that, armed as adults, has a better chance of applying for more important jobs.
In Scotland, different languages will be dealt with in each school.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while many will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance to the United Kingdom by 2020.
Whatever the interests of the child, he will learn several optional languages from independent schools and will be trained by instructors who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that prepares and provides them with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future may save.
It is not difficult to see that, in the current global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of a country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should be treated as "international communication skills".
Independent schools offer the possibility of choice, diverse and quality education to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
