Harvard students are trained to rest enough
A new subject at Harvard University this year encouraged students to sleep more, also fighting against the increasingly gaining macho culture of caffeine-heated all-night learning.
An academic concluded that students from the world's number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he believes is the first such training in the U.S., was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard College of Medicine and practises as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He was encouraged to develop the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I only facing this now as a senior?’
He said no one ever told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
During the course launched for the first time this year, students are told how the right sleep patterns have a fundamental impact on their educational and sports performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their general well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard College of Medicine and director of the university's health service, the university decided to start the course because during the week students were found to be extremely unsleepy.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is influenced by sleeplessness, and why bedtime routines have significance.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the university area with interactive icons is presented to encourage participants to consider the daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change student behavior.
But we believe that they have a right to these knowledge – just as they have the right to be aware of the health effects of smoking," said Professor Czeisler.
The culture in which learning through a night is a achievement continues to flourish, he said, adding that modern technology and constantly increasing pressure on students results in increasing problems of sleep deprivation.
Sufficient and quality sleep is a student's “secret weapon” in the struggle with stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even protects from obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into a starving mode and causes a continuous sense of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, and took one of the professor's courses as a freshman at Harvard last year.
He said that what he heard there had opened his eyes and encouraged him to fight for the launch of a university-level training course.
He hoped that as a next step, postgraduate students would be able to participate in a similar training program before settling into the competitive sphere.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning for bedtime, an alarm to wake up, and familiarize themselves with the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily dissuade them from the daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
