A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” abnormal cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" and destroy abnormal cells
A vaccine given as part of a treatment teaches the immune system to recognise abnormal cells.
Part of the method is to extract the immune cells from the patient and then modify them in a lab.
This enables them to “see” the protein that accompanies a variety of cancers. Treated immune cells are injected back into the patient.
An experimental vaccine has yielded promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system how to detect abnormal cells could say goodbye to ovarian cancer for over 18 months.
It is part of the method of extracting immune cells from the patient; it is modified in the laboratory to ‘see’ a protein called HER2 that is a common accompaniment to several cancers; then to replant the cells.
Jay Berzofsky, a professor at the American National Cancer Research Institute, Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "stimulates the growth of multiple types of cancer," including breast, ovarian, lung and rectum cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar method, based on highlighting immune cells and "teaching" them how to attack cancer cells, has previously been used successfully to treat a type of leukemia.
