HIV/AIDS: China’s number of new patients increased by 14%
China has announced that the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS in the country has increased by 14%.
Health officials have said that this means more than 820,000 people involved.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, the number of reported cases increased by approximately 40,000.
A change from previous ones is that a significant majority of newly infected people are sexually exposed to the disease.
The disease used to spread rapidly through the transfusion of infected blood in parts of China.
Health officials, however, stated at a conference in the province of Junnan that the number of such cases had since fallen to nearly zero.
Nevertheless, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000 compared to the previous year.
The sexual transfer of HIV is a serious problem for the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality has not been a crime in China since 1997, but discrimination against the community has been very strong ever since.
Based on estimates in various studies, 70-90% of men who have sexual relations with other men end up marrying women due to the country's conservative values.
In many cases the disease spreads in these relationships due to inadequate sexual protection.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to anti-HIV medicines as part of a programme to solve the problem.
