What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it managed to reduce poverty?
The annual music event in New York City, the Global Citizen Festival, will begin on Saturday. World stars will perform at the festival to stand up for a truly noble goal: global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival is now held for the seventh time, and tens of thousands of people are expected to fill Central Park's Great Plant, where participants will not only be able to enjoy Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes' performance, but will also be able to draw attention to the real purpose of the event: eradicating deep poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizens Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project. The project is run by an international advocacy group aimed at eradicating poverty by involving more and more people active in the fight against poverty.
Free tickets to the concert (unless they are willing to pay for VIP tickets) can be given to those who undertake to perform certain tasks or "acts", such as volunteering, sending emails to a leading politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity to raise awareness for the purpose of the project: eradicating poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen actually been in achieving the goals set over the last 12 years?
Is it really an effective means of rewarding people with concert tickets to convince others of the importance of action, or is this just another form of so-called "cliquetivism" when people feel they have actually contributed to a case by signing or writing an online petition?
Since 2011, Global Citizen figures show that more than 19 million "acts" have been carried out by project promoters serving many different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions contributed to the allocation of $37 billion by world leaders to policies and commitments against poverty that could affect the lives of over 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group claimed 390 commitments and announcements were from their actions, $10 billion of which had already been paid or collected during fundraising.
The group estimates that the money collected has already had a direct impact on the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership between investors and contractors to "help children achieve their inherent potential". The organization promised Rwanda $35 million to help eradicate starvation after receiving over 4,700 Twitter messages from "global citizens".
"With the support of the UK government and donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can banish social injustices and malnutrition among footnotes in history books," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition to the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after asking the United Kingdom for more than 5,000 actions to improve the food of mothers and their children, the government allocated funds to the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve food for 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions published on the Global Citizen's website is: "Why do you think deep poverty can be eliminated?".
The Global Citizen replied: “It will be a long and difficult journey, in which we sometimes get stuck and sometimes fail.
But like earlier civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we achieve our goal because together we are stronger."
Among other things, Janet Jackson, Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe will perform at this year's New York event, and the hosts will be Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
