The inventor of the World Wide Web would launch a new Internet to confront Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup with the aim of competing with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project in technological legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
With Solid, users can choose where they want to store their data and who can access individual information.
In his exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was to "acquire control of the world."
“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
– It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "personal online repository", also known as POD.
This may include lists, to-do lists, calendars, music library, as well as other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are available from the same browser at the same time.
The unique thing about the personal online repository is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access your data.
The company calls this "the realization of the right of individuals to self-determination over data".
According to John Bruce, CEO of Inrupt, the company is responsible for providing resources, processes, and appropriate skills to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contract developers working in the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week onwards, world technology developers can create their own decentralised applications using devices available on the Inrupt site.
Berners-Lee said he and his team would not ask "Facebook and Google to introduce full-change technology that would completely turn the business models of companies upside down overnight."
"We don't ask permission from them."
In the entry published on the Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the newly built network on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at Massachusetts Technical University.
Berners-Lee has been an important opinion-former in recent months in discussions surrounding the neutrality of the Internet.
Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute despite the launch of Inrupt.
"I am endlessly optimistic about the next era of the World Wide Web," added Berners-Lee.
