The National Trust is searching for the secret life of bats
New research is underway on a Scottish-Highland estate aimed at finding out how bats exploit landscape features during hunting.
Researchers hope to gain new information about the behaviour of single flying mammals from the results, which may also benefit from subsequent species conservation initiatives.
Scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will investigate the behavior of common and soprano dwarf bats, as well as brown long-eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Garden area in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at the appropriate points of the area to record bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will be using handheld detectors to collect mobile data.
Detailed analysis of the recording audio can determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species are doing.
Researchers also make habitat maps and reports to determine in detail how animal behaviour is shaped depending on landscape.
Rob Dewar, NTS conservation advisor, hopes that the results will show what are the most important habitats for bats and how any species uses them.
This information helps to determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as the development of meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have fallen considerably over the last century.
Construction and landscaping work disrupt animals' sleeping areas and reduce their living space.
Wind turbines and street lighting are also a risk factor for them, as are flypapers placed, certain chemical processes used for building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really completely blind.
However, because of their nightly predatory nature, they rely much more on their hearing when hunting prey than on their sight.
By using their sophisticated technique based on the reflection of ultrasound, they can determine the exact position of insects as well as the landmarks on their way.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings across the country, 38 gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land, takes bats issue very seriously.
They work with ten qualified professionals who regularly conduct studies and sleeper studies and occasionally participate in rescue work.
The organization established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threate estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
According to estate manager David Thompson, the area is an ideal habitat for bats.
“Here, in Threade, bats have a great place, ” he said.
– There are old buildings, lots of old trees, and everything else needed for a good living space.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats yet, and thanks to the work done here and in other similar areas, we can learn more about what they need to feel good about themselves."
He also highlighted the importance of making sure that bats live there before the renovation of buildings, as destroying a single colony could result in the destruction of 400 females and young individuals, which could lead to extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals, their destruction, harassment, and habitat tampering are prohibited by law.
Elisabeth Ferrell, representative of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, also requested the help of the population.
He said: “There is still much we do not know about bats, and we have almost no information on the situation of the population of most domestic species."
