Red tide news: Concentration declines in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentration in some areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, more spotted flowering has been reported from the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The extent of the red tide is roughly 130 miles of coastline, from the northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
About 10 miles from the outskirts of Hillsborough County there are spots, but compared to last week there are relatively smaller areas.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and along its coast, low to high concentrations along the coasts of Hillsborough County, from background to high concentrations in Manatee County, from background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and along its coast, from background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, from background to high concentrations in Lee County and along its coast and low concentrations in Collier County.
There were still reports of respiratory irritation in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritation from northwestern Florida.
